So this evening, really, it's the turn of Vipassana.

18
00:01:39,356 --> 00:01:48,165
And I'm only reinforcing what I'm sure most of you know, but it's always good to go over sort of basics.

19
00:01:51,466 --> 00:01:56,792
The first thing is to really grasp what the Buddha means by this right awareness.

20
00:01:57,143 --> 00:02:24,518
um i think we have to go back you know i do mention his moment in in childhood where um he's watching his father doing a prong ceremony and after his ascetic practices that becomes a memory which gives him some sort of inspiration and what he recognizes was that as a child he was

21
00:02:24,784 --> 00:02:51,366
equally absorbed he could very quickly go into an absorption because the heart's very pure as a child usually and um but there was something extra which he had not been practicing he had been uh practicing the jhana which is really about establishing very beautiful intense mental states but there's no wisdom there that's what he eventually discovered

22
00:02:52,122 --> 00:02:58,692
And this memory from childhood, I think, inspired him and gave him a different angle.

23
00:02:58,872 --> 00:03:06,584
So instead of trying to achieve happiness, I think he then sat down and wondered how he was creating suffering.

24
00:03:06,604 --> 00:03:16,819
There were points before that when he was investigating that, such as the time he felt fear, such as the time he realized that there were two types of thoughts.

25
00:03:16,979 --> 00:03:19,563
One was wholesome and one was unwholesome.

26
00:03:20,067 --> 00:03:27,977
That was the beginning, really, of recognising that at the root of our problems is ethics, our relationships.

27
00:03:29,800 --> 00:03:40,894
And that, of course, was very novel for the time, remember, because people presume that misfortune and all the rest of it partly happened because of the gods or fate or something like that.

28
00:03:41,549 --> 00:03:44,673
The Buddha really wasn't into fate as such.

29
00:03:45,774 --> 00:04:01,033
Of course, things happen not simply because of my own personal actions, but eventually what happens within me, my own mental state, the inner world, my subjective world, is something that I'm creating.

30
00:04:01,615 --> 00:04:09,564
And he discovered how not only the heart could be healed, but how there was something that actually was beyond

31
00:04:10,085 --> 00:04:13,788
that lay beyond the body and mind.

32
00:04:15,151 --> 00:04:22,298
So I always think it's good when we're a bit confused about what we mean by right awareness, just to go back to that little child.

33
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:28,865
All of us will have had that moment of seeing a bug or something or a beetle and asking our parents where it is.

34
00:04:29,487 --> 00:04:39,838
But there will have been a moment there where, you know, like children, their eyes fix on it and you can see they're completely absorbed, they lose

35
00:04:40,189 --> 00:04:42,572
even if you talk to them, they don't hear you.

36
00:04:42,713 --> 00:04:45,197
You know, they're completely absorbed in what they're looking at.

37
00:04:45,216 --> 00:04:46,418
And of course, the jaw drops.

38
00:04:46,458 --> 00:04:46,999
Remember that?

39
00:04:47,079 --> 00:04:48,300
Yes, they look gormless.

40
00:04:48,982 --> 00:04:58,314
And that tends to be a reason why your parents, you know, give you a little tap on the shoulder or in the old days, a smack across the head.

41
00:04:59,194 --> 00:05:07,446
I remember one woman telling me that her father used to tell her to keep her mouth shut and a fly would get in there.

42
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:37,163
the whole point of course is that with the relaxed jaw there's no thinking there's no coming from a position from some idea from some concept and that's what opens up this intelligence we have this intuitive awareness to receiving stuff and of course the intelligence is within within the awareness so it makes insights because remember what happens is the child then having absorbed

43
00:05:37,379 --> 00:05:41,163
the little bug, will turn to the parent and say, you know, what is it?

44
00:05:41,603 --> 00:05:44,185
And mummy will say, well, that's a beetle, you see.

45
00:05:44,204 --> 00:05:52,192
So already the child has a photocopy, a perception of this, a percept of this little bug.

46
00:05:52,452 --> 00:05:59,560
And every time it sees one from now on, it's not interested in actually seeing that as an individual little creature.

47
00:06:00,040 --> 00:06:01,701
It's interested in naming it.

48
00:06:02,442 --> 00:06:03,824
And so it says, oh, there's a beetle.

49
00:06:04,084 --> 00:06:05,125
And mummy says, oh, very

50
00:06:05,829 --> 00:06:16,586
So how to get back to the original mind, what Zen often calls original mind or beginner's mind.

51
00:06:16,846 --> 00:06:17,687
That's our problem.

52
00:06:18,470 --> 00:06:26,161
And of course, the noting technique in the Mahasi tradition is meant to occupy the thinking mind.

53
00:06:26,182 --> 00:06:30,267
We're meant to see through the word towards the object.

54
00:06:30,569 --> 00:06:58,264
uh to the feeling of something right so we're moving off concepts of percepts of perception and moving down into the visceral part of our experience which is the body the feelings in the body and now the heart is expressed and felt in the body you know it's not anger for instance uh you know we often just splurt it out with bang doors and silly stuff like that but when you sit with it

55
00:06:58,480 --> 00:07:00,723
there's a completely different experience.

56
00:07:01,764 --> 00:07:06,692
And you're allowing the heart to, of course, clear itself.

57
00:07:06,711 --> 00:07:11,639
So, you know, whenever we're lost about, well, what is this meditation about?

58
00:07:11,858 --> 00:07:13,422
You know, just go back to that child.

59
00:07:13,862 --> 00:07:18,428
Just watch, just feel, just experience.

60
00:07:18,449 --> 00:07:22,615
Of course, now this intuitive awareness has been instructed.

61
00:07:22,966 --> 00:07:29,112
It sort of knows within itself what it's looking at, the cause of suffering, desire, impermanence.

62
00:07:29,132 --> 00:07:30,415
But you don't have to keep telling it.

63
00:07:30,475 --> 00:07:37,603
You don't have to keep doing it purposefully because when you do it purposefully, you're putting some sort of idea in the way.

64
00:07:38,303 --> 00:07:50,677
So it is quite difficult for us just to get into that very relaxed, at ease, focused position of just watching, just feeling, just experiencing.

65
00:07:52,649 --> 00:08:00,399
Now, when you get there, you see after, when you come out or when the mind shoots off or something, you come back, remind yourself, right?

66
00:08:00,420 --> 00:08:01,442
How did I get there?

67
00:08:01,682 --> 00:08:03,204
Right.

68
00:08:03,225 --> 00:08:09,853
And, and, and, and reflect on the quality of that pure watching, because that's how you'll get back to it more and more easily.

69
00:08:10,095 --> 00:08:11,136
Yeah.

70
00:08:11,156 --> 00:08:20,088
That's of course, uh, so long as life doesn't become horrendous as it has been for me in the past hour, trying to get this streaming correct.

71
00:08:21,752 --> 00:08:21,812
Um,

72
00:08:24,560 --> 00:08:35,490
So the second thing is to begin to understand how we work with these hindrances, you know, to be very clear about that.

73
00:08:36,412 --> 00:08:40,355
And finally, I won't go into that detail.

74
00:08:41,157 --> 00:08:42,116
There's many talks on it.

75
00:08:43,278 --> 00:08:45,520
And finally, seeing these three characteristics.

76
00:08:45,620 --> 00:08:50,405
Again, these things you can, you know, there are talks, hundreds of talks about it.

77
00:08:50,426 --> 00:08:53,688
But what I want to talk about is this awareness.

78
00:08:54,073 --> 00:09:01,662
and to give some other images that help us to perceive what this awareness is.

79
00:09:03,884 --> 00:09:07,168
The first thing is, and the process of meditation.

80
00:09:07,509 --> 00:09:11,111
So the first thing is to go back to being to the baby again.

81
00:09:11,172 --> 00:09:22,764
So we're told that within the first three, four months of our lives, it's just a shower of information, light, sounds, touches, feelings, tastes,

82
00:09:23,065 --> 00:09:25,167
and can't make head or tail of it really.

83
00:09:25,847 --> 00:09:35,677
But slowly out of that mass of information, your first object arises, your carer, your mother, obviously more often than not.

84
00:09:39,601 --> 00:09:44,346
But of course, the one thing the baby does know is that what is pleasant and unpleasant.

85
00:09:44,506 --> 00:09:46,369
I mean, I think we're born with that.

86
00:09:47,950 --> 00:09:50,692
So as over the next,

87
00:09:50,875 --> 00:09:57,821
A year or more or whatever, the baby pushes out this outer world, separates from it.

88
00:09:58,782 --> 00:10:02,764
And so the outer world begins to manifest with its three dimensions.

89
00:10:03,245 --> 00:10:05,187
And it's moving away from it.

90
00:10:05,267 --> 00:10:08,850
It's finding itself in another position to it.

91
00:10:09,730 --> 00:10:19,919
And psychologically, of course, it doesn't really liberate itself from that intense connection with the mother till about three years old, something like that anyway.

92
00:10:20,203 --> 00:10:29,437
So at the age of three, the little child has a very great sense of me and with it there comes not me.

93
00:10:30,679 --> 00:10:36,349
So they push that outer world out and it's become not me and this is who I am.

94
00:10:36,389 --> 00:10:41,196
Now, in our practice, that's all we are doing internally.

95
00:10:41,296 --> 00:10:48,506
We're now pushing the internal world out, as it were, into an object to observe.

96
00:10:48,706 --> 00:10:56,746
When we see sensations, the observer, the feeler, is observing it as an object.

97
00:10:57,568 --> 00:11:03,846
When we feel emotions, the observer, the feeler, the experiencer, is feeling it as an object.

98
00:11:04,552 --> 00:11:31,621
And so by doing so, this awareness, which has been confused in what the Buddha would call the five aggregates, the psychophysical organism, is slowly pulling itself out and making these five aggregates, the body, feelings, all perceptions, thoughts, and all our habits, and even consciousness as an object.

99
00:11:33,239 --> 00:11:40,308
So now that's, of course, very confusing because most people would say, these days anyway, that you are your consciousness.

100
00:11:40,769 --> 00:11:50,144
You are what you are aware of without making that distinction between awareness and consciousness as a screen upon which everything happens.

101
00:11:50,904 --> 00:11:54,750
So how do we know that the Buddha talks about it as a screen?

102
00:11:54,770 --> 00:12:00,899
Because even in the scriptures, the Buddha is not so, the use of words in the scriptures

103
00:12:01,235 --> 00:12:05,879
varies according to who he's talking to and what he's trying to say.

104
00:12:06,640 --> 00:12:14,669
But at the point of contact, what we have is a physical base, an object, and consciousness.

105
00:12:14,730 --> 00:12:22,938
So consciousness becomes the screen upon which we can see things, the screen upon which we hear things.

106
00:12:23,340 --> 00:12:26,263
It's a moment of cognition, you might say.

107
00:12:26,547 --> 00:12:31,774
I don't really know what the proper word in English is because they also have various meanings.

108
00:12:32,475 --> 00:12:34,236
But if you think of a screen, you see.

109
00:12:35,759 --> 00:12:41,307
Now, with that in mind, I like to use the myth of Narcissus.

110
00:12:41,447 --> 00:12:43,529
Now, Narcissus is a beautiful young man.

111
00:12:43,629 --> 00:12:44,912
He looks into the pool.

112
00:12:44,932 --> 00:12:46,133
He falls in love with his image.

113
00:12:46,494 --> 00:12:48,756
He goes to embrace it and drowns.

114
00:12:49,697 --> 00:12:54,985
And this is normally understood to be, you know, self-love, pride,

115
00:12:55,251 --> 00:13:06,402
or whatever, but it works perfectly spiritually because the awareness, as it were, looks into that screen and it mirrors back its own presence.

116
00:13:06,422 --> 00:13:07,864
That's your first object.

117
00:13:08,985 --> 00:13:09,946
I am aware.

118
00:13:09,966 --> 00:13:11,326
I am me.

119
00:13:11,706 --> 00:13:13,749
That sense of me being the awareness.

120
00:13:14,470 --> 00:13:21,917
And then, as it were, through that very same screen, it falls into the world of make-believe of the mind.

121
00:13:22,419 --> 00:13:25,764
And in mythology, usually water is creation.

122
00:13:26,804 --> 00:13:45,769
So if you can imagine the awareness waking up in the morning, catching its presence in the mirror and knowing itself, and then immediately falling into the make-believe world, alarm clock, get up, go to work, et cetera, et cetera.

123
00:13:46,470 --> 00:13:50,014
That's happening really many times during the day.

124
00:13:51,445 --> 00:13:59,214
But that distinction is extremely subtle and very difficult to actually directly experience.

125
00:13:59,735 --> 00:14:01,736
But it can be experienced.

126
00:14:01,756 --> 00:14:08,905
And there's a point in your practice when you're very, very still, very, very quiet.

127
00:14:09,405 --> 00:14:13,772
The body's very still, the heart's very calm, the mind is quiet.

128
00:14:14,192 --> 00:14:19,258
And the sense of the observer, the sense, the feel of the observer is very strong.

129
00:14:19,745 --> 00:14:23,270
the feel of the feeler, the experiencer.

130
00:14:24,052 --> 00:14:30,121
You're right there with that self-awareness, self-awareness.

131
00:14:31,063 --> 00:14:39,597
And as it were, you've almost separated out the awareness from all the stuff on the screen.

132
00:14:40,118 --> 00:14:42,883
And if you can just, as it were, glance back,

133
00:14:43,994 --> 00:14:49,380
Or has it, yes, glance back or, yeah, that's about the best I can say.

134
00:14:50,802 --> 00:14:52,004
Other teachers use the same.

135
00:14:52,163 --> 00:14:55,928
It's mainly a little Mahayana technique.

136
00:14:56,109 --> 00:14:58,471
And then ask yourself, well, what's in there?

137
00:14:58,511 --> 00:15:00,934
What constitutes the awareness?

138
00:15:01,655 --> 00:15:04,139
Do I find any sensations, any feelings?

139
00:15:04,200 --> 00:15:08,825
Are there any emotions or moods or any thoughts or images, you see?

140
00:15:09,385 --> 00:15:13,191
And in that way, we're starting to realize this unique quality

141
00:15:13,389 --> 00:15:16,793
of our Buddha nature, our intuitive awareness.

142
00:15:18,395 --> 00:15:21,779
So that's one process.

143
00:15:22,500 --> 00:15:25,163
There are many ways people can have insights.

144
00:15:25,183 --> 00:15:29,950
They can have insights directly through seeing the process of desire.

145
00:15:30,409 --> 00:15:33,433
That can also be a moment of liberation.

146
00:15:34,455 --> 00:15:35,875
And the same with impermanence.

147
00:15:36,256 --> 00:15:41,423
So this is more like a moment of understanding, of clear understanding,

148
00:15:41,621 --> 00:15:44,664
through the process of anatta, not me, not mine.

149
00:15:47,408 --> 00:15:51,152
So with that image, let me see the time.

150
00:15:51,533 --> 00:15:52,413
Oh, I'm not doing so bad.

151
00:15:52,432 --> 00:15:56,278
I think it's, oh yes, that's right.

152
00:15:56,837 --> 00:16:10,852
With that image and the image of the child and the whole idea of getting into a position of just watching, just feeling, just experiencing, then...

153
00:16:11,203 --> 00:16:14,028
Now we're clearer about the practice that we're doing.

154
00:16:21,498 --> 00:16:22,740
Well, I'm afraid that's it.

155
00:16:23,221 --> 00:16:39,523
So I can only hope my words have been of some service, that you aren't even more confused, and that by your devotion to practice, you will be liberated sooner rather than later.

156
00:16:40,582 --> 00:16:42,942
So I think we can do a little bit of practice.

157
00:16:43,690 --> 00:16:44,113
Very good.

